			<tr><td colspan="2"><hr /></td></tr>
			<tr><td colspan="2">
				<div class="postbody">
				I think it is about time to drill in Alaska.  Alaska is a big %@$# state, I don't think the caribou would mind if we put down a few wells here and there.  It also seems to appear that people (Stylx amongst them) think that if you drill and lay down pipelines you have to do so destructively.  That is not the case.  Sure during the actual construction process there will be some heavy machinery, but after it gets rocking and rolling there will be only very minor impacts on the environment.
<br />
I live in Texas.  We have a few oil wells around here.  In fact they are now going hog wild drilling in Fort Worth tapping into some huge reserve.  The impact of those new wells is minuscule, people don't even notice most of them.
<br />

<br />
I think drilling in Alaska and money earmarked for petroleum research is good in terms of a stop-gap measure however the government really needs to push more nuclear power (@#%$ what the liberal hippy douches say) and other alternative fuels for a long term solution.
<br />

<br />
In terms of loosening up the environmental restrictions, this is a good thing - unless you are a hippy.  The US has, as far as I know, the most strict environmental policies in the world.  Hell ours our much more strict than Japan's, which is one reason why the Kyoto Accord is nothing but a crock @#%$.  Anyhow, it was interesting in that a few days ago the Saudi Crown Prince's spokesman almost wigged out on the American public stating that Saudi Arabia has been trying to send more oil to the US but our environmental standards are too strict to allow that additional oil to be refined.  Damn liberals want it both ways, and look where it has gotten us.
<br />

<br />
This MTBE issue is another crock @#%$.  For years I used to perform what we called a MBTEX (MTBE, Benzene, Toluene, Ethylbenzenes, p/m Xylene) analysis which was a method per EPA SW846 8015/8021.  As far as I knew then, there was no data at all to support any carcinogenic effects of MTBE.  Sure it can be labeled as a "possible carcinogen" but just about everything in the world has that label.  I can damn well guarantee that your computer and monitor contains much more carcinogens and is more toxic for you than the toxicity of MTBE in your gas tank.  I believe the LD50 of water is something like 15 liters.  Anything is a poison, it just depends on the dose.
<br />
People are also under the impression that MTBE can get into lakes and stick around for a while.  When I use to analyze MTBE we would have it weighed up in methanol (MeOH) in a volumetric flask with ground glass joints, i.e. @#%$ was in a closed container.  We would have to make new solution everyday because the MTBE would evaporate out of the MeOH and still find a way out of the volumetric flask.  I couldn't imagine how fast MTBE would evaporate out of a lake under the sun.  My point is, it ain't sticking around for long.
<br />

<br />
MTBE, as far as I can tell, is just a whipping boy that people like to cite hoping that it sounds evil @#%$.<br />
				<span class="gensmall"></span><br />
				</div>
