</span><table width="90%" cellspacing="1" cellpadding="3" border="0" align="center"><tr> 	  <td><span class="genmed"><b>Quote:</b></span></td>	</tr>	<tr>	  <td class="quote">Authorizes more than $3 billion annually to help poor families pay winter heating bills.</td>	</tr></table><span class="postbody"> Pork that ends up in the energy companies pockets. Why not just hand them a check for $3Billion? Oh? We want to pretend to be useful and launder it by <span style="font-style: italic">helping</span> the poor. Like Enron and their cronies when they <span style="font-style: italic">helped</span> California by writing the electricity deregulation bills, and then <span style="font-style: italic">helping</span> California by manipulating the system, creating artificial blackouts and <span style="font-style: italic">helping</span> themselves to about $20Billion in extra profit.
<br />

<br />
</span><table width="90%" cellspacing="1" cellpadding="3" border="0" align="center"><tr> 	  <td><span class="genmed"><b>Quote:</b></span></td>	</tr>	<tr>	  <td class="quote">Eases environmental constraints to build or expand oil refineries in economically depressed areas. </td>	</tr></table><span class="postbody"> What a load of baloney. Oil companies have been staging <span style="font-style: italic">accidents</span> and <span style="font-style: italic">maintenance shutdowns</span> to keep the spot market up. Refineries in CA spend about 4-5 months per year <span style="font-style: italic">not working</span>. If the Saudi excuse is that the USA lacks refining capacity, why not operate the plants all year long instead of 3/4 of the time? 
<br />

<br />
</span><table width="90%" cellspacing="1" cellpadding="3" border="0" align="center"><tr> 	  <td><span class="genmed"><b>Quote:</b></span></td>	</tr>	<tr>	  <td class="quote">Limits product liability for makers of methyl tertiary butyl ether (MTBE), a fuel additive and suspected carcinogen that has fouled groundwater in cities across the nation</td>	</tr></table><span class="postbody"> Translation: we poisoned counties and turned some into Love Canals, and we want to protect our contributors and prevent them from paying for their crimes.
<br />

<br />
</span><table width="90%" cellspacing="1" cellpadding="3" border="0" align="center"><tr> 	  <td><span class="genmed"><b>Quote:</b></span></td>	</tr>	<tr>	  <td class="quote">Cuts number of special gasoline blends now required to ease air pollution in cities and regions. </td>	</tr></table><span class="postbody"> Actually a good one. There are a lot of these blends that aren't significantly different from each other.
<br />

<br />
</span><table width="90%" cellspacing="1" cellpadding="3" border="0" align="center"><tr> 	  <td><span class="genmed"><b>Quote:</b></span></td>	</tr>	<tr>	  <td class="quote">Extends expiring accident insurance protection for owners of nuclear power plants by 20 years.</td>	</tr></table><span class="postbody"> If we had some Chernobyl sized catastrophy, nuke plant operators are limited by statute to something like $500,000,000 liability. If everyone in your county had to permanently abandon their homes, divide half a billion dollars by the number of homes in your county to get an idea of how much you'd lose.
<br />

<br />
The reactor designs in the USA are intended to create lots of plutonium. The original economics of nuclear plants was to make plutonium to sell to the Federal Government (for about $1,000 per gram). That sale of plu would pay for the construction, operation and decomissioning of the plants, with a reasonable profit margin as well. Electricity would be a by-product, which is why the head of the AEC kept claiming that nuclear power would be too cheap to meter. In 1970, the US Government quit purchasing privately produced plutonium (basically, they said "we have enough nukes, thx, la~"). There are about 1,700 tons of plutonium in private ownership in the USA (the feds have about 100 tons of plutonium spread amongst all the nuclear weapons and assembly plants). That is nearly 2 trillion dollars that the power industry <span style="font-style: italic">didn't</span> get paid for in the last 35 years.
<br />

<br />
Offering "low liability insurance" won't magically make nuclear power plants economical. It takes huge subsidies. Refining and enriching the uranium to use in our reactors takes massive amounts of electricity. So much so that it wasn't until the mid 1970s when the nuclear power industry made more electricity than it used. Some of the diffusion plants in Hanford needed more electricity than a nuclear power plant could produce.
<br />

<br />
</span><table width="90%" cellspacing="1" cellpadding="3" border="0" align="center"><tr> 	  <td><span class="genmed"><b>Quote:</b></span></td>	</tr>	<tr>	  <td class="quote">Spends $1.3 billion for experimental Idaho reactor that would also produce hydrogen fuel. </td>	</tr></table><span class="postbody"> Pork, pork, pork. Sit there in your porkness and be pork.<br />
