</td>	</tr></table><span class="postbody">
<br />

<br />
Well, that's the stick.  How about the carrot?  I'm hazy on the details, but as I understand it, no one really owns that infrastructure, yet everyone gets to use it and are suppose to take care of it.  Sound a little Marxian?  If someone specifically owned it, and made a profit from it being in good working order, it would be in good working order.</td>	</tr></table><span class="postbody">
<br />
[/quote]
<br />

<br />
Their disadvantaged users ONLY have a contract with their provider.  Their provider is liable to them REGARDLESS of what infrastructure they utilize.  It is on the provider to collect from whomever it is contracted with.  Therfore when 50,000 lose power, the company or companies that &gt;they&lt; pay are responsible for the loss.
<br />

<br />
Most utility contracts do NOT garuntee power.  So if you want to raise a stink the place to do it is with your city or municipal government  that contracts power supply.  Make them put up-time garuntees in the contract.
<br />

<br />
If you cant get to yahoo from your home, you don't call Level3 you call your isp or line provider with whom you have a contract.<br />
